WEBVTT

00:00:01.229 --> 00:00:05.429
Millions of our brothers and sisters around the world can recount the blessings they've

00:00:05.429 --> 00:00:10.189
gained by remaining loyal to Jehovah and his organization.

00:00:10.189 --> 00:00:14.310
And we're privileged to have two such examples here with us today.

00:00:14.310 --> 00:00:18.809
Brother and sister William and Sandra Melonfont, brother Melonfont is a helper to the teaching

00:00:18.809 --> 00:00:23.550
committee and sister Melonfont's current assignment is in the service department.

00:00:23.550 --> 00:00:27.989
And we're looking forward to hearing about their rich spiritual history.

00:00:27.989 --> 00:00:32.509
Bill and Sandra were so happy that we could have you here in the studio with us and we

00:00:32.509 --> 00:00:35.509
do look forward to learning more about you.

00:00:35.509 --> 00:00:37.030
Maybe we'll have to go back.

00:00:37.030 --> 00:00:42.109
How did you get on the road that has led you to such many years of faithful loyal service

00:00:42.109 --> 00:00:43.109
to Jehovah?

00:00:43.109 --> 00:00:45.829
It was back in 1954.

00:00:45.829 --> 00:00:49.390
My mother had contact on and off with the witnesses for years.

00:00:49.390 --> 00:00:54.950
I was about 20 years old and she was invited to a public talk at the Oakland Central

00:00:54.950 --> 00:00:58.829
congregation in California and she asked me, would you accompany me?

00:00:58.829 --> 00:01:02.030
And I said, yeah, sure, I'll be happy to go.

00:01:02.030 --> 00:01:06.670
Well, I recognized a young man I knew from high school at the meeting and he approached

00:01:06.670 --> 00:01:10.109
me after and told me I needed a Bible study.

00:01:10.109 --> 00:01:15.790
I really didn't want a Bible study but he insisted and so I said, well, you can come by.

00:01:15.790 --> 00:01:16.790
Would you believe it?

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:21.150
I started a Bible study in the Let God be true book.

00:01:21.150 --> 00:01:22.950
Four months later I was baptized.

00:01:22.950 --> 00:01:26.870
It was exactly what I was looking for and I didn't realize it.

00:01:26.870 --> 00:01:27.870
Excellent.

00:01:27.870 --> 00:01:31.870
Now, I understand that you were also very involved with sports.

00:01:31.870 --> 00:01:38.709
Yes, I was playing ball for a basketball team in Alameda and I enjoyed very much playing

00:01:38.709 --> 00:01:44.230
ball but then a decision came up as to what I was going to do because the evenings when

00:01:44.230 --> 00:01:49.469
the team played was the same time that we had the service meeting under theocratic ministry

00:01:49.469 --> 00:01:50.469
school.

00:01:50.469 --> 00:01:55.950
Like a decision and my decision was forget the sports and let's go to the meetings and

00:01:55.950 --> 00:01:57.909
enjoy being built up spiritually.

00:01:57.909 --> 00:01:58.909
Good choice.

00:01:58.909 --> 00:01:59.909
Thank you.

00:01:59.909 --> 00:02:03.909
Sandra, your start on the road to a career serving Jehovah.

00:02:03.909 --> 00:02:08.270
I suppose you could say that it actually started before I was born.

00:02:08.270 --> 00:02:12.590
Before I was born, my parents started on this search for the truth.

00:02:12.590 --> 00:02:16.949
It happened because they had lost a little girl in death and they went from church to

00:02:16.949 --> 00:02:19.870
church looking for some kind of comfort.

00:02:19.870 --> 00:02:22.069
And of course, the clergy had no comfort for them.

00:02:22.069 --> 00:02:28.069
They just said, well, God wanted another angel in heaven and that angered my father.

00:02:28.069 --> 00:02:31.389
He thought, no, if God wants another angel, he can make one.

00:02:31.389 --> 00:02:33.629
He wouldn't take my little girl.

00:02:33.629 --> 00:02:39.629
So it just happened that one evening they were listening to the radio long before TV,

00:02:39.629 --> 00:02:40.870
of course.

00:02:40.870 --> 00:02:46.669
And they heard a Jehovah's Witness give a talk and then the title of that talk was Where

00:02:46.669 --> 00:02:47.990
Aren't They Dead?

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:48.990
Imagine.

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:54.349
He gave all the scripture proof about the condition of the dead, the hope for the resurrection.

00:02:54.349 --> 00:02:58.509
And my father immediately said, this is the truth.

00:02:58.509 --> 00:03:04.469
So they wrote to the radio station, got a copy of the booklet of the talk.

00:03:04.469 --> 00:03:09.710
And then also they started receiving the subscription to the watch tower.

00:03:09.710 --> 00:03:14.310
But it wasn't until I was born in three years old that the witnesses finally made contact

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:15.310
with us.

00:03:15.310 --> 00:03:16.310
Interesting.

00:03:16.310 --> 00:03:19.069
It was a real cold winter day.

00:03:19.069 --> 00:03:23.909
And even though I was only three years old, I remember this family coming in and they

00:03:23.909 --> 00:03:25.509
stayed hours.

00:03:25.509 --> 00:03:28.590
I even hid in the closet and went sleep.

00:03:28.590 --> 00:03:33.750
But you know, it was just, it was that contact with the visible organization that my family

00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:36.189
needed because they knew much of the truth.

00:03:36.189 --> 00:03:39.349
They'd been reading the watch tower for a long time.

00:03:39.349 --> 00:03:44.030
So my elder sisters, they got baptized right away and started pioneering.

00:03:44.030 --> 00:03:47.909
For my brother and I, we were a lot smaller, of course.

00:03:47.909 --> 00:03:52.189
We just went along with our parents and came right into the truth.

00:03:52.189 --> 00:03:57.590
In fact, I remember was just a couple of years later that we were all going to go to the

00:03:57.590 --> 00:04:03.069
big convention in 1950 at Yankee Stadium.

00:04:03.069 --> 00:04:05.669
But I knew there was going to be a big baptism there.

00:04:05.669 --> 00:04:09.030
But I wanted to go as a baptized Jehovah's Witness.

00:04:09.030 --> 00:04:14.990
So my father, everybody made arrangements and my father baptized me in our pond on our

00:04:14.990 --> 00:04:18.029
farm with another young sister.

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:19.470
So that was my beginning.

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:23.350
You know, Ron, there's a point I'd like to recall also.

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:28.470
Sandra was at a special convention back in 1941.

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:29.470
That's true.

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:30.470
Even before that.

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:35.350
That was probably my first, you know, big event, theoretically.

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:40.470
Our family, my brother was four years older than I, along with my parents.

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:47.430
So we went to the St. Louis Convention where brother, Rathapur gave his famous talk on

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:48.430
children.

00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:54.589
And they separated the lower level of this place that they rented, the stadium was dedicated

00:04:54.589 --> 00:04:59.350
to just the young children, well, from five to 18 years of age.

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:04.589
And it was just fantastic, you know, this man, when you're small, this man would look

00:05:04.589 --> 00:05:08.350
so big and huge and he had this great, big voice.

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:14.310
And I'll never forget when he looked out on the audience and he said, be whole more than

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:17.829
15,000 new witnesses to the kingdom.

00:05:17.829 --> 00:05:18.829
So it was very emotional.

00:05:18.829 --> 00:05:20.029
Oh, you still remember it like it?

00:05:20.029 --> 00:05:21.029
Oh, yes.

00:05:21.029 --> 00:05:22.029
It happened yesterday, right?

00:05:22.029 --> 00:05:23.029
How exciting.

00:05:23.029 --> 00:05:28.110
So what motivated you to make a choice to get into the full-time service and give your

00:05:28.110 --> 00:05:29.870
life to Jehovah?

00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:35.550
Well, what motivated me was when I attended a convention also in 56.

00:05:35.550 --> 00:05:37.790
I got baptized in 54.

00:05:37.790 --> 00:05:42.629
But in 56, I went to a district convention in Albany, California and there was a pioneer

00:05:42.629 --> 00:05:46.990
booth because in those days they had a booth set up at the district conventions and various

00:05:46.990 --> 00:05:51.230
brothers and sisters would man the booth and answer your questions about pioneer service.

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:55.790
So I approached the booth and an older sister there looked at me and said, you're young

00:05:55.790 --> 00:05:57.709
and strong, why aren't you a pioneer?

00:05:58.430 --> 00:06:01.230
Well, I felt, well, yes, why not?

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:03.910
So I started pioneering in 1956.

00:06:03.910 --> 00:06:07.069
That's what motivated me and I was, really, I looked back at that.

00:06:07.069 --> 00:06:09.949
It was one of the best decisions I made in my life.

00:06:09.949 --> 00:06:10.949
Excellent.

00:06:10.949 --> 00:06:11.949
Yeah.

00:06:11.949 --> 00:06:15.750
So you have been making wise decisions from your youth, Sandra, how about you?

00:06:15.750 --> 00:06:18.149
Motivating to put in a full-time service.

00:06:18.149 --> 00:06:22.029
Well, for a pioneer service, you know, it was like a given.

00:06:22.029 --> 00:06:26.509
Young people were just encouraged to pioneer and you knew that when you graduated from high

00:06:26.509 --> 00:06:32.230
school, you started out pioneering and most of the young people were doing that.

00:06:32.230 --> 00:06:35.910
You know, after a year or two, maybe they would get married and start a family, but those

00:06:35.910 --> 00:06:41.709
years and pioneering, starting out their life that way, gave them a wonderful basis for

00:06:41.709 --> 00:06:44.670
loyal service, the rest of their life.

00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:51.029
And not only that, I remember that in those days, the traveling overseer would stay in

00:06:51.029 --> 00:06:54.430
the homes of the brothers when he served the congregation.

00:06:54.430 --> 00:06:58.350
And we always played host to the circuit overseer and his wife when they came.

00:06:58.350 --> 00:07:01.350
And from my brother and I, they were role models.

00:07:01.350 --> 00:07:05.750
My sisters, as I told you, were out pioneering in another assignment.

00:07:05.750 --> 00:07:11.550
But for us, these brothers were so full of zeal and they were like heroes to us.

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:16.910
In particular, I remember when I was, I think about 12 years old, this couple came around

00:07:16.910 --> 00:07:19.990
on the circuit, Percy and Ilma Islam.

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:24.269
They were also from Australia, and of course, we love their accent, too.

00:07:24.269 --> 00:07:28.709
And they had just graduated from Gilead and they were assigned to Japan.

00:07:28.709 --> 00:07:31.870
But they had to wait a number of months to get their visa.

00:07:31.870 --> 00:07:34.430
They served in our congregation.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:39.069
And it was really them that instilled in me the desire to become a missionary.

00:07:39.069 --> 00:07:40.470
Beautiful.

00:07:40.470 --> 00:07:42.310
So you were pioneering.

00:07:42.310 --> 00:07:45.029
How did your paths eventually meet?

00:07:45.029 --> 00:07:51.470
It was at a circuit assembly in Oakland, California, 1956.

00:07:51.470 --> 00:07:53.470
Very interesting things took place.

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:56.629
I had the job of dismantling the stage.

00:07:56.629 --> 00:07:58.230
I had not yet met Sandra.

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:03.470
She was out visiting her sister who lived in the same area where I was.

00:08:03.470 --> 00:08:08.110
And I was carrying this large piece of plywood off the stage and I ran right into Sandra and

00:08:08.110 --> 00:08:09.949
knocked her flat.

00:08:09.949 --> 00:08:11.870
Well I took advantage of the opportunity.

00:08:11.870 --> 00:08:14.990
I thought, well, that's not the best way to introduce yourself.

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:19.470
But I said, by the way, would you like to accompany me to a get-together, some of the

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:22.709
friends are having and she accepted.

00:08:22.709 --> 00:08:24.189
And very good, Bill.

00:08:24.189 --> 00:08:25.189
Well, yes.

00:08:25.189 --> 00:08:26.189
And I followed through on it.

00:08:26.189 --> 00:08:30.949
We had a lot of association and after a number of months, we got married.

00:08:30.949 --> 00:08:34.870
And both of us were pioneering, very happy in our ministry serving Jehovah.

00:08:34.870 --> 00:08:37.070
You really swept her off her feet, literally.

00:08:37.070 --> 00:08:38.070
I felt for it.

00:08:38.070 --> 00:08:39.070
Very good.

00:08:39.070 --> 00:08:43.269
So shortly after you were married, I understand you received some direction.

00:08:43.269 --> 00:08:44.269
Yes.

00:08:44.269 --> 00:08:47.190
And the circuit overseer visited our congregation.

00:08:47.190 --> 00:08:50.750
We were only married about a month, I think, when he came through.

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:55.590
And he told us that the organization was looking for pioneers who'd be willing to serve

00:08:55.590 --> 00:09:01.470
a special pioneers and go wherever where the need was great in the United States, particularly.

00:09:01.470 --> 00:09:05.029
So we told them, sure, we'd be delighted to do it.

00:09:05.029 --> 00:09:10.350
And four months after our marriage, we received an assignment as special pioneers to Ducora

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:11.669
Ayua.

00:09:11.669 --> 00:09:17.230
Now that was a very interesting place because there were only eight publishers in the congregation.

00:09:17.230 --> 00:09:20.870
But we arrived, started with the meetings there at the Kingdom Hall.

00:09:20.870 --> 00:09:25.470
And the Kingdom Hall was up above Hunt's Variety Store in downtown Ducora.

00:09:25.470 --> 00:09:28.149
And we lived in a room behind it.

00:09:28.149 --> 00:09:32.830
Well, sometimes, especially during the winter time, because it could be very cold.

00:09:32.830 --> 00:09:36.190
There'd be no one at the meeting after all, there were only eight publishers.

00:09:36.190 --> 00:09:40.590
But I was insisting that no, I'm going to give my public talk.

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:41.870
Whether anyone's here or not.

00:09:41.870 --> 00:09:46.309
So I'd tell Sally, you sit there and I give my public talk, a one hour talk.

00:09:46.309 --> 00:09:50.590
And then I'd conduct the watchtower study and have her answer every question.

00:09:50.590 --> 00:09:52.830
Well, you know, you're on your own like that.

00:09:52.830 --> 00:09:54.590
Not a lot of brothers around.

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:56.669
So you look for encouragement and company.

00:09:56.669 --> 00:10:03.110
And we would travel down to Strawberry Point, Ayua, to where Charles and Shirley Sonnetco

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:06.470
lived in a log cabin, one room log cabin.

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:10.149
And we'd go visit with them in order to have some mutual encouragement.

00:10:10.309 --> 00:10:12.309
And because they were special pioneering also.

00:10:12.309 --> 00:10:14.110
OK, well, you were both special.

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:18.389
Yeah, it's a nice picture of you in that log cabin too, as you were special pioneering.

00:10:18.389 --> 00:10:20.070
So you're busy in that work.

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:22.789
What special invitation did you receive?

00:10:22.789 --> 00:10:29.029
Well, we received the invitation to attend Gillian, the 34th class of Gillian School.

00:10:29.029 --> 00:10:31.110
And that was a wonderful thing.

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:34.909
After two and a half years of pioneering, special pioneering in Ayua,

00:10:34.909 --> 00:10:40.110
our instructors were Albert Schroeder, Maxwell Friend, Bob Porter,

00:10:40.389 --> 00:10:42.110
and Jack Redford.

00:10:42.110 --> 00:10:46.710
And we had a delightful time at Gillian, as you can imagine.

00:10:46.710 --> 00:10:49.149
And we were assigned to Lebanon.

00:10:49.149 --> 00:10:53.269
But we were unable to enter Lebanon because we couldn't get the visa.

00:10:53.269 --> 00:10:57.789
So then the organization asked us, well, will you take an assignment to Morocco?

00:10:57.789 --> 00:10:59.230
We were ready to go anywhere.

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:04.230
We're pioneering with the Canarcy congregation just waiting to go out into the field.

00:11:04.230 --> 00:11:10.070
So that's how we took a boat from New York City five days across the Atlantic to Casablanca.

00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:11.509
Very nice.

00:11:11.509 --> 00:11:15.629
What was it like to be in the missionary service in Morocco?

00:11:15.629 --> 00:11:17.029
It was very interesting.

00:11:17.029 --> 00:11:18.269
We really enjoyed it.

00:11:18.269 --> 00:11:19.909
But you know, we only spoke English.

00:11:19.909 --> 00:11:22.750
So in Morocco, we had to learn French.

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:27.389
And the first month of our missionary service in Morocco was for 30 days.

00:11:27.389 --> 00:11:30.830
You studied the language 11 hours a day.

00:11:30.830 --> 00:11:33.350
Well, that could get pretty tiring for 11 hours a day.

00:11:33.350 --> 00:11:37.190
So we'd go to the French movies and count that as language time.

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:39.309
And then we were moved to Tangier.

00:11:39.309 --> 00:11:41.590
And there was a Spanish congregation in Tangier.

00:11:41.590 --> 00:11:44.669
And so we had to learn the Spanish language too.

00:11:44.669 --> 00:11:50.190
But that was really a rich blessing for the two of us to be exposed to that culture

00:11:50.190 --> 00:11:52.590
and to have that privilege of serving there.

00:11:52.590 --> 00:11:57.110
But you know, what I really enjoyed, we had a variety of people we preached to.

00:11:57.110 --> 00:12:00.389
We had a very large Jewish population.

00:12:00.389 --> 00:12:02.590
And they were almost all Orthodox.

00:12:02.590 --> 00:12:05.470
But you know, they were very forthright.

00:12:05.470 --> 00:12:08.549
And they were open and quite curious.

00:12:08.549 --> 00:12:11.429
You know, like they'd come to us sometimes and say,

00:12:11.429 --> 00:12:13.230
well, you're Christian, aren't you?

00:12:13.230 --> 00:12:15.990
Why do you accept Jesus as the Messiah?

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:19.389
So we had to get familiar with a lot of scriptures, you know,

00:12:19.389 --> 00:12:23.750
that dealt with the prophecy that Messiah would fulfill in the Hebrew scriptures.

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:25.549
And really, it was a delight.

00:12:25.549 --> 00:12:29.389
Sandra, remember, there were a lot of French people in Morocco

00:12:29.389 --> 00:12:32.190
because it used to be a colony under France.

00:12:32.190 --> 00:12:35.470
So that's why the French language was so important.

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:39.389
And then we had Spanish people and many other nationalities there.

00:12:39.389 --> 00:12:43.470
So you had four years of serving in Morocco, faithfully,

00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:46.110
loyally meeting all those different languages,

00:12:46.110 --> 00:12:47.909
learning the language yourself.

00:12:47.909 --> 00:12:52.389
So after four years, I understand that you came back to visit your family.

00:12:52.389 --> 00:12:55.389
What events were challenging thereafter?

00:12:55.389 --> 00:12:57.909
I think Sandra can relate that.

00:12:57.909 --> 00:13:02.629
Well, it was usually permitted after you and your assignment four years.

00:13:02.629 --> 00:13:07.110
Then you were allowed to come home at least to have a vacation, visit your family.

00:13:07.110 --> 00:13:09.909
And so we made arrangements to come back.

00:13:09.909 --> 00:13:14.110
We got some tickets on a Yugoslav freighter,

00:13:14.110 --> 00:13:16.990
took us two weeks to get back to New York.

00:13:16.990 --> 00:13:19.309
But we got back, we visited our family.

00:13:19.309 --> 00:13:23.830
And while there, I had a medical examination

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:26.230
and found out that I had a serious health problem.

00:13:26.230 --> 00:13:28.429
Of course, we didn't have the funds to cover that.

00:13:28.429 --> 00:13:30.750
So Bill wrote to the society.

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:32.309
And we made arrangements.

00:13:32.309 --> 00:13:35.190
They said, we'll just take care of your situation

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:37.429
and let us know when you're free.

00:13:37.429 --> 00:13:43.230
So he got a job to take care of our medical needs as well as living conditions.

00:13:43.230 --> 00:13:46.990
But you know, we just felt like we were failures.

00:13:46.990 --> 00:13:49.190
I'd always wanted to be a missionary.

00:13:49.190 --> 00:13:51.750
And there we were four years at our assignment.

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:55.509
We come back and plough. We're just there.

00:13:55.509 --> 00:13:58.070
But you know, Jehovah knew we were discouraged.

00:13:58.070 --> 00:14:00.710
He knew we felt distraught about this.

00:14:00.710 --> 00:14:02.830
So he knew just what we needed.

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:04.470
And he gave it to us.

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:10.110
As I got to feeling better and we got more free in our use of time,

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:15.429
we started pioneering and Jehovah blessed our ministry just incredibly.

00:14:15.429 --> 00:14:20.470
There were times in this supposedly unproductive territory

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:23.590
that we had up to 25 people attending the meetings.

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:27.230
Many of them got baptized and there are fast friends to this day.

00:14:27.230 --> 00:14:31.230
That's incredible. So Jehovah knows what you need and he provides it.

00:14:31.230 --> 00:14:33.509
That is beautiful.

00:14:33.509 --> 00:14:36.830
What temptation did you have to resist when you came back

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:38.350
and going through these difficulties?

00:14:38.350 --> 00:14:43.110
I think it's a temptation that confronts a lot of brothers and sisters

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:45.350
who return because of health reasons.

00:14:45.350 --> 00:14:50.149
And some just end up settling down because of their circumstances.

00:14:50.149 --> 00:14:52.710
But the temptation there was, well, your home,

00:14:52.710 --> 00:14:56.389
you've already done your service in Morocco for a number of years.

